$PLTR...I had pre-IPO shares. In spite of the S-1 indicating PLTR has never been profitable I knew there was a lot of hype and speculation around the name. My entire premise was predicated upon timing of the IPO. Not fundamental.  Coming to market at a time of unprecedented cheap money supply and a Fed induced, artificial expansion was key. Although valuations never made since during that moment in time, eventually the math has to add up.  As reflected by the repricing of all Tech names, the math is finally adding up.   PLTR opened around $10 and experienced a killer Plandemic run to $45.  Sold! There's a legit argument to be made about how to value certain companies (Street Games) but in the final analysis price is the ultimate judge and jury. It's a reflection of all traders/investors buying and selling in real time.  In the case of PLTR, coupled with insider selling and a lack of institutional interest, purgatory indefinitely.  Unless you're Cathie Wood with a 5 year time horizon.

$EPAM.....EPAM Systems, Inc (NYSE:EPAM) reported second-quarter FY22 revenue growth of 35.6% year-on-year to $1.195 billion, beating the consensus of $1.12 billion. Acquisitions completed in the last twelve months contributed 6.2% to revenue growth. 
Non-GAAP income from operations was $177.5 million, up 14.3% Y/Y. The non-GAAP operating margin contracted 270 bps to 14.9%. 
Non-GAAP EPS of $2.38 beat the consensus of $1.72. 
EPAM held $1.296 billion in cash and equivalents.
